    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-12-14T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-12-14T20:00:00-05:00" n="602"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d602">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.111 Vessels/5103: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Consul General at Hamburg</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Erhardt</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-12-14T20:00:00-05:00"
                            >December 14, 1933—8 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <p>Repeat following to Consul General at Berlin: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Advise by mail supervisory consular officers in European countries and
                            at London for information offices under their supervision as follows:
                            Labor Department holds alien seamen traveling as passengers or
                            transients for purpose transferring at American port to another vessel
                            for service as members of crew are not admissible for this purpose.
                            Therefore visas, crew list visas, or transit certificates should not be
                            issued by American consuls, except as provided in Notes 84 and 85
                            section 361 Consular Regulations. Any alternate plan which may be
                            suggested by a steamship company should be reported to the Department
                            for instruction.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
